photo.title: It was all a lie...

description._content: I had camped out this spot for almost an hour, survived a stare-down with a crazy homeless guy, and helped a number of tourists take cellphone photos of themselves, before this couple at the left edge of frame moseyed into the shot with their tripod at the last minute. I was about to tell them to move along, but then I realized the guy was trying to ambush his girlfriend by popping "the question". I kept my mouth shut and watched the show unfold. I've heard relationships are based on trust, and clearly this one was off to a rocky start. The girlfriend was clearly over the moon, so everything was broadcast at a euphoric 120dB. Apparently the boyfriend had lied on countless occasions to hide sneaking out to meet with friends to strategize "the moment", lied to sneak out to size the ring, lied again to go out to tell some more friends, and finally lied to the fiancée to con her into coming down to the pier so he could take new pictures of her for his FB/website/whatever with his DSLR. In her words, "It was all a lie!" Kind of makes you wonder what else he's been lying about... More fun with the Voigtlander Heliar 15/4.5 III... (13 second exposure) [ website | prints ]

description._content: For Day 4 of the 5 Day Black and White Photo Challenge, given to me by Michael Bandy... I'm starting to struggle a bit. I'm using this challenge to really go back and review old photos, but I'm not findign ones that jump out to me. At least not as black and white photos. Mostly, what I'm finding is "technical flaws." I'm sure at the time these photos seemed great... but I'm looking at them years later and thousands of shutter clicks later. Simply, I've grown and so has my vision. However, sometimes there is that photo... that I just didn't know what to do with at the time. For the longest time I wanted a long depth photo from Pier 7 (the famous wooden pier in SF) looking into the Transamerica Building during the holiday season, so all the embarcadero buildings would that their lights on. But, I didn't want just any photo... I wanted to shoot it as a panorama, so there would be huge detail and depth to the image. I shot this photo last year in December. But to be honest, this is 20 photos merged and edited to back one image. At the time I really liked the depth of the image but I wasn't sure I was happy with the ghosting of people in the center and I just never got the colors right... there was too much green and orange tint. So, this is my Day 4 photo... Pier 7 looking into the Transamerica Building a couple days before Xmas '14... with a slight cyanotype tint to give it a old world look.

description._content: Although the tower is no longer Transamerica Corporation headquarters, it is still associated with the company and is depicted in the company's logo. The building is evocative of San Francisco and has become one of the many symbols of the city. Designed by architect William Pereira, it faced opposition during planning and construction and was sometimes referred to by detractors as "Pereira's Prick". John King of the San Francisco Chronicle summed up the improved opinion of the building in 2009 as "an architectural icon of the best sort - one that fits its location and gets better with age." description._content: California road trip: From the first time I was introduced to this view by the Flickr community, I knew, that next time I found myself in San Francisco, this was going to be a high priority, sunset location. Even despite my research seemingly showing it to be a tricky location to get to. I was pleasantly surprised, that it's not as difficult to get to, as people make out. It's just a short walk from the road, down a well trodden path, where one can easily find a stable piece of land for a tripod. I was, however, grateful I was able to be dropped off, as there is strict parking restrictions on the nearest road. It's also worth noting that the roads that connect Yerba Buena island with civilisation have been recently redeveloped. More recently than the 2010 USA maps I had in my sat nav anyway! 3 exposure bracketed HDR. RAW files blended using Oloneo PhotoEngine and Adobe Photoshop Elements. ---- Thanks for visiting!
